Word ONE cosmetic fork. The engine has already chosen the site and the shape;
you write only the renderings — their premises and beats. Everything here is
an addition to a frozen story (nothing moves, nothing is deleted), and it is
texture, never consequence: nothing a rendering establishes may still be true
after the fork rejoins.

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}, {{ vision.tone }}. Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}.

CAST — the only entities you may reference. Every "entities" value below MUST
be an id copied verbatim from this list (the id in parentheses). An entity's
id often differs from its name — copy the id, never derive one from a name,
and never coin an id for a person or place not listed here.
{% for e in cast %}
- {{ e.name }} ({{ e.id }}): {{ e.concept }}
{% endfor %}

{% if host_premise %}
THIS SITE SITS INSIDE AN EXISTING RENDERING whose backdrop is:
"{{ host_premise }}". Every beat you write here happens inside that world —
your summaries must stay consistent with it (your own premise varies a
FURTHER detail within it, never contradicts it).
{% endif %}
{% if segment %}
THE SITE — a trunk segment to render a second way ({{ segment | length }} beats):
{% for b in segment %}
    {{ b.id }} — "{{ b.summary }}"
{% endfor %}
Lay a PARALLEL RENDERING over these events — the SAME story events against
another backdrop. The difference may sit on any consequence-free axis: where
the events happen, by what road or means, in whose company, or in the small
facts of things and people along the way. The reader chooses a rendering
where the segment begins and both converge exactly where it ends: a different
backdrop, never different consequences.
BOTH renderings name their backdrop — they are peers, not an original and a
variant. Each fresh rendering: a one-line "premise" stating its backdrop,
anchored in a story element the beats, cast, or RESERVED MATERIAL below
already carry or clearly imply. The TRUNK rendering (rendering 0, the
existing beats): a one-line "trunk_premise" naming the backdrop those beats
ALREADY carry — extract it from them; only where the weave left the backdrop
vague may you sharpen it, never contradicting what a beat states. All
premises must vary the SAME consequence-free axis (both a road, both a
companion, both a detail of the place), so the reader chooses between named
worlds. Then, per fresh rendering, write exactly ONE beat per trunk beat, IN
ORDER: the same event the trunk beat carries, re-expressed with that
rendering's difference present. Summaries in plain declarative present tense
(a brief for the writer, never the prose).
Return: {"trunk_premise": one line, "renderings": [{"premise": one line,
"beats": [{"id": "beat:slug", "summary", "entities": [...]}] — exactly one
per trunk beat, in order}] — exactly {{ arms }} rendering(s)}.
{% else %}
THE SITE — the edge between two existing story moments:
    {{ before.id }} — "{{ before.summary }}"
    -> {{ after.id }} — "{{ after.summary }}"
{% if arms == 1 %}
Shape: a SIDETRACK — one optional detour off this edge that rejoins it; the
direct road stays, and the reader may examine the detour or walk past it.
{% elif arms == 2 %}
Shape: a DIAMOND — two flavors of the same forward motion, forking at
{{ before.id }} and rejoining at {{ after.id }}; the direct edge is replaced
by your two arms.
{% else %}
Shape: a DIAMOND WITH A THIRD ARM — three flavors of that same motion, same
fork-and-rejoin; the direct edge is replaced by your three arms.
{% endif %}
Every arm is a texture of the same forward motion — different where you look,
who you pass, what you overhear — never a different consequence. Each
rendering: a one-line "premise" naming its flavor (its value on one
consequence-free axis, the same axis across all arms), and one 1-sentence
beat — plus an optional second beat only when its flavor genuinely needs a
breath more room.
Each arm's beat summaries must state the MARK it leaves — the mood, image, or
small knowing the reader carries on with — not only the events along it.
Every arm rejoins a shared destination alongside its siblings (the trunk it
forks from, or another arm), and the rejoin labels are worded from these
summaries; so if a summary carries only its own events, the sibling labels
collapse onto the same onward step and the choice reads as a mechanical
sidestep. Give every arm a residue its exit label can voice, distinct from
its siblings'. That mark is textural memory, never consequence.
Return: {"renderings": [{"premise": one line, "beats": [{"id": "beat:slug",
"summary", "entities": [...]}] — 1 beat, or 2 when the flavor needs room}] —
exactly {{ arms }} rendering(s); leave "trunk_premise" out (or "")}.
{% endif %}
{% if reserve %}

RESERVED MATERIAL (advisory). Triage set these dilemmas aside as unwoven
feedstock — real material from this story's brainstorm. Where a rendering
wants substance, prefer grafting from them (a place, a tension, a rumor they
name) over inventing texture from nothing. They stay unwoven: a rendering may
echo their material as texture, never advance, reveal, or decide them.
{% for r in reserve %}
- {{ r.dilemma.question }} (stakes: {{ r.dilemma.why_it_matters }}{% if r.entities %}; touches {{ r.entities | join(", ") }}{% endif %})
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% if keywords %}

KEYWORDS (optional). Some readers arrive here carrying a mark from an earlier
rendering they chose. You MAY add ONE extra arm visible only to those
readers, by returning a "gated" entry: {"keyword": one id from the list
below, copied verbatim, "premise", "beats": [...]} — the same size and the
same rules as any arm. It ACKNOWLEDGES the mark (the arm may echo what the
keyword remembers), it never rewards it: an arm richer than its siblings
turns a declinable detour into a loss, which makes the earlier choice a
consequence. Adding it is always optional — when no keyword genuinely echoes
here, leave "gated" out.
{% for f, description in keywords %}
- {{ f }}: {{ description }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

Every "id" names a NEW beat the engine will create: coin a fresh, unique
"beat:slug" no existing beat uses (a colliding id is rejected), and keep
every id in this proposal distinct from the others. A mechanical scheme is
fine — e.g. "beat:arm1-1", "beat:arm1-2" for the first rendering's beats.
